1
00:00:07,298 --> 00:00:10,885
[Claire] I want a Declaration, Roger.
So we can send them in.

2
00:00:10,969 --> 00:00:14,097
<i>- </i>[Roger] <i>But, Madam President...</i>
- I have the Guard, FEMA and the EPA

3
00:00:14,180 --> 00:00:16,808
mobilized and waiting
on the outskirts of that town.

4
00:00:16,891 --> 00:00:18,685
<i>I just got off the phone
with the refinery.</i>

5
00:00:18,768 --> 00:00:20,895
<i>The leak is well on its way
to burning off.</i>

6
00:00:21,813 --> 00:00:24,733
My understanding is that the air quality
is dangerous.

7
00:00:24,816 --> 00:00:27,110
The levels are somewhat elevated, yes,

8
00:00:27,193 --> 00:00:30,155
- but the winds are in our favor.
<i>- And subject to change.</i>

9
00:00:30,238 --> 00:00:31,823
<i>That's how wind works.</i>

10
00:00:31,906 --> 00:00:34,075
This will all be over in a day or two,

11
00:00:34,159 --> 00:00:36,661
the idea of keeping these families out
of their homes...

12
00:00:36,745 --> 00:00:38,663
<i>This is a prudent precaution</i>

13
00:00:38,747 --> 00:00:41,332
<i>and on my watch,
that’s what I want to happen.</i>

14
00:00:41,416 --> 00:00:43,418
I don’t think we should
exaggerate the situation.

15
00:00:46,504 --> 00:00:48,840
Do you remember where you were
on election night, Governor?

16
00:00:50,383 --> 00:00:51,676
<i>Because I do.</i>

17
00:00:52,135 --> 00:00:53,970
<i>You were going to lose.</i>

18
00:00:54,846 --> 00:00:58,933
Statistically, there is no reason
you should have won.

19
00:01:02,479 --> 00:01:04,957
<i>Keep the phone away from your mouth
while you’re thinking, Governor.</i>

20
00:01:04,981 --> 00:01:06,357
<i>I can hear you breathing.</i>

21
00:01:07,984 --> 00:01:08,984
Yes.

22
00:01:11,196 --> 00:01:14,824
I do believe I need to declare
a state of emergency.

23
00:01:17,118 --> 00:01:19,287
Of course, it's your call.

24
00:01:20,163 --> 00:01:22,874
And I assure you,
you will have the full support

25
00:01:22,957 --> 00:01:24,292
of the federal government.

26
00:01:26,878 --> 00:01:30,048
I promised myself I wouldn't be like him.

27
00:01:30,381 --> 00:01:32,383
That was textbook Francis, wasn't it?

28
00:01:33,259 --> 00:01:37,097
But he handed me over to them
like a shaker of salt

29
00:01:37,180 --> 00:01:38,807
and now they won't let go.

30
00:01:40,517 --> 00:01:42,936
This is a wound of their own making.

31
00:01:46,314 --> 00:01:47,607
Mr. Vice President?

32
00:01:50,860 --> 00:01:51,860
[Mark] Yeah, come in.

33
00:01:55,532 --> 00:01:56,866
Do you need a moment, sir?

34
00:01:57,200 --> 00:01:59,244
No, no.

35
00:02:00,036 --> 00:02:01,036
What is it?

36
00:02:05,875 --> 00:02:06,875
Okay. Governor?

37
00:03:48,937 --> 00:03:50,188
[man] They said it was fine.

38
00:03:50,647 --> 00:03:54,400
It smelled like rotten eggs and trash.
That’s all.

39
00:03:54,484 --> 00:03:56,486
You could smell it coming out
of the faucet.

40
00:03:56,903 --> 00:04:00,323
And then my son, his...
his nose started to bleed and I thought,

41
00:04:00,406 --> 00:04:02,687
- "Is that related?"
- Where is your little boy right now?

42
00:04:02,742 --> 00:04:05,370
Now? He's in triage with his mom.

43
00:04:06,120 --> 00:04:09,499
- He's my heart, that little guy.
- No, I know. I know.

44
00:04:10,083 --> 00:04:11,584
But, ma'am. If I may. You...

45
00:04:11,668 --> 00:04:13,836
You have to tell us.
Is this real or not?

46
00:04:13,920 --> 00:04:16,798
Because at first they said that
we don't need to evacuate,

47
00:04:16,881 --> 00:04:18,067
and then all of a sudden that we should.

48
00:04:18,091 --> 00:04:20,852
I want you to know everything
is going to be all right. I promise you.

49
00:04:20,885 --> 00:04:23,680
[man] We were relying on that plant
to keep us informed.

50
00:04:23,763 --> 00:04:25,390
Sir, you and your safety

51
00:04:26,140 --> 00:04:27,642
is the most important thing.

52
00:04:27,725 --> 00:04:30,770
In fact, all of the families of Bellport,

53
00:04:31,604 --> 00:04:33,231
nothing else matters.

54
00:04:34,232 --> 00:04:36,693
I want to give my thanks
to Governor Olmstead

55
00:04:36,985 --> 00:04:39,279
for his quick and decisive act
this morning

56
00:04:39,362 --> 00:04:41,239
in declaring a state of emergency.

57
00:04:41,572 --> 00:04:44,117
We have FEMA, we have EPA,

58
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:46,286
the Ohio National Guard.

59
00:04:46,369 --> 00:04:47,537
They're all here.

60
00:04:48,413 --> 00:04:51,374
No one should ever feel unsafe.

61
00:04:52,375 --> 00:04:53,751
In her own home.

62
00:04:54,961 --> 00:04:59,041
[Bill] <i>And how is it you have no idea, Mark?</i> -[Annette] <i>It doesn't matter.</i>
- [Bill] <i>Oh, it does matter.</i>

63
00:04:59,799 --> 00:05:01,926
<i>It speaks to this untenable arrangement.</i>

64
00:05:02,010 --> 00:05:04,470
[Annette]<i> Later, I said. Let’s stay</i>
<i>focused on our response.</i>

65
00:05:04,554 --> 00:05:06,389
She was all set to sign the bill
this morning.

66
00:05:06,472 --> 00:05:08,659
We had photographers,
a press pool waiting, the whole thing.

67
00:05:08,683 --> 00:05:11,412
- [Bill] <i>But she didn't sign it, did she?</i>
- [Annette] <i>I'm on my way there now.</i>

68
00:05:11,436 --> 00:05:14,814
Because she was too busy manufacturing
an emergency out of nothing.

69
00:05:14,897 --> 00:05:17,483
[Mark] <i>Look, let’s not forget</i>
<i>who escalated this. Okay?</i>

70
00:05:17,567 --> 00:05:18,568
Excuse me?

71
00:05:18,651 --> 00:05:20,278
<i>If we're working together, Bill,</i>

72
00:05:20,361 --> 00:05:22,447
<i>I need to be included in every decision.</i>

73
00:05:22,780 --> 00:05:24,574
<i>Every one.</i>

74
00:05:24,657 --> 00:05:26,200
[Bill] <i>This conversation's over.</i>

75
00:05:26,284 --> 00:05:28,119
Oh, for God's sakes.

76
00:05:28,202 --> 00:05:29,682
[Mark] <i>I'll join Annette in Bellport.</i>

77
00:05:29,746 --> 00:05:30,955
[Bill] <i>No, you won’t.</i>

78
00:05:31,039 --> 00:05:32,957
<i>One of you showing up on site
is bad enough.</i>

79
00:05:33,041 --> 00:05:34,917
- Annette, call me back.
- [phone beeps]

80
00:05:35,001 --> 00:05:36,044
[sighs]

81
00:05:36,794 --> 00:05:37,794
Mark.

82
00:05:38,087 --> 00:05:39,422
Mark, are you still there?

83
00:05:40,673 --> 00:05:41,673
Yes.

84
00:05:42,050 --> 00:05:44,260
<i>Let me talk to him. I'll circle back.</i>

85
00:05:49,265 --> 00:05:52,393
[inhales, exhales]

86
00:05:57,940 --> 00:05:59,275
<i>Hello, everyone.</i>

87
00:06:00,568 --> 00:06:02,195
My name is Kelsey Stewart.

88
00:06:02,653 --> 00:06:04,489
I'm the deputy press secretary,

89
00:06:04,572 --> 00:06:06,699
and I will be taking your questions today.

90
00:06:07,742 --> 00:06:08,742
Sarah.

91
00:06:09,035 --> 00:06:11,079
Is it true that Governor Olmstead
was resistant

92
00:06:11,162 --> 00:06:12,955
to declaring a state of emergency?

93
00:06:13,039 --> 00:06:15,541
<i>The Governor did declare
a state of emergency,</i>

94
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:16,834
and the White House concurs.

95
00:06:16,918 --> 00:06:18,795
Something very wrong happened
in that plant.

96
00:06:19,253 --> 00:06:20,253
Yes.

97
00:06:20,296 --> 00:06:24,425
Arcas has been slow to provide any details
when it comes to the leak and explosion.

98
00:06:24,509 --> 00:06:26,469
Not to mention the two lives lost
in the accident.

99
00:06:26,552 --> 00:06:28,888
Have they been cooperating
with the White House?

100
00:06:28,971 --> 00:06:30,765
Now that the president is on the ground,

101
00:06:30,848 --> 00:06:33,309
it seems that, yes,
they have been more agreeable.

102
00:06:33,935 --> 00:06:36,479
Uh...
That's not the real question, though.

103
00:06:37,271 --> 00:06:40,858
<i>Somebody might want to ask, where is
Shepherd Unlimited in all of this?</i>

104
00:06:40,942 --> 00:06:44,320
<i>The Arcas Refinery is a subsidiary
of the family’s conglomerate.</i>

105
00:06:44,404 --> 00:06:47,407
[woman] <i>Are you saying that the Shepherds</i>
<i>are personally aware</i>

106
00:06:47,490 --> 00:06:48,741
<i>of problems at the plant?</i>

107
00:06:49,117 --> 00:06:50,952
<i>Who is responsible and how</i>

108
00:06:51,035 --> 00:06:54,122
<i>is all the White House and the president
are trying to find out at this point.</i>

109
00:06:54,205 --> 00:06:55,665
[clamoring]

110
00:06:55,748 --> 00:06:56,874
Will this have any effect

111
00:06:56,958 --> 00:06:59,252
on the regulatory bill
on the president's desk?

112
00:06:59,335 --> 00:07:01,254
The president will be speaking
on that shortly.

113
00:07:01,796 --> 00:07:02,796
Marcus.

114
00:07:03,047 --> 00:07:05,883
Was the president planning
to divorce the former president

115
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:08,094
in the days leading up to his death?

116
00:07:10,721 --> 00:07:12,807
Uh, let's...

117
00:07:13,641 --> 00:07:15,685
- Oh. Mr. Vice President.
- Morning, everyone.

118
00:07:15,768 --> 00:07:18,396
I hope Miss Stewart won’t mind me
taking a couple of questions.

119
00:07:18,479 --> 00:07:20,559
[clamoring]
[woman] Mr. Vice President, one question!

120
00:07:22,233 --> 00:07:23,734
[Usher] Marcus, who's your source?

121
00:07:24,026 --> 00:07:26,779
- [Marcus] Unnamed officials.
- Nope. We don't do that anymore.

122
00:07:26,863 --> 00:07:28,531
We need names. You have a name?

123
00:07:29,031 --> 00:07:31,451
I mean really, where do you get this?

124
00:07:31,909 --> 00:07:32,910
The former president

125
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:35,413
spent his last night alive

126
00:07:35,496 --> 00:07:37,216
next to his wife in the White House.
Period.

127
00:07:37,248 --> 00:07:38,624
As for Bellport...

128
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:41,770
let’s not jump to conclusions
before all the facts are in.

129
00:07:41,794 --> 00:07:42,795
What else?

130
00:07:43,296 --> 00:07:45,631
We still going door to door,
but it's really a precaution.

131
00:07:46,215 --> 00:07:47,633
Are there enough beds?

132
00:07:47,717 --> 00:07:51,012
We have a few church basements
and the local jail if we need more.

133
00:07:51,095 --> 00:07:54,182
Whatever hydrogen sulfide there is left
in the air is already dissipating.

134
00:07:54,265 --> 00:07:56,785
[man] In a day or two, people will be back
sleeping in their own beds.

135
00:07:56,809 --> 00:07:58,144
[man 2] You have to understand,

136
00:07:58,394 --> 00:07:59,854
Madam President,

137
00:08:00,062 --> 00:08:03,232
most everyone overreacts
when it comes to chemicals.

138
00:08:03,524 --> 00:08:05,193
We have years of experience...

139
00:08:05,276 --> 00:08:07,153
And the men who died in the accident?

140
00:08:07,236 --> 00:08:10,573
That's tragic, of course.
They were valued employees.

141
00:08:10,656 --> 00:08:13,701
Members of the community.
There's no way to replace them.

142
00:08:13,784 --> 00:08:15,286
And Bill Shepherd?

143
00:08:16,120 --> 00:08:18,164
- Yes.
- Have you heard from him?

144
00:08:19,081 --> 00:08:22,335
I've kept him informed,
as well as all of our partners.

145
00:08:22,418 --> 00:08:25,838
Bill called me directly.
They're ready to do whatever's needed.

146
00:08:26,088 --> 00:08:27,465
They're important to Bellport.

147
00:08:27,548 --> 00:08:30,235
They built the local stadium.
Even this gymnasium. They contributed...

148
00:08:30,259 --> 00:08:32,303
No, I’m well aware
of the family’s philanthropy.

149
00:08:32,386 --> 00:08:33,679
That wasn't the question.

150
00:08:33,763 --> 00:08:37,725
Yes, Mr. Shepherd has been monitoring
the situation closely.

151
00:08:37,808 --> 00:08:39,435
I would like to tour the area.

152
00:08:41,938 --> 00:08:44,440
Is that a problem, Governor?

153
00:08:45,024 --> 00:08:47,443
No, no, not to my understanding.

154
00:08:48,402 --> 00:08:50,780
I was hoping to get you over to...

155
00:08:50,863 --> 00:08:52,448
to where we set up our triage.

156
00:08:52,532 --> 00:08:54,384
It might be best
if we stick to the itinerary...

157
00:08:54,408 --> 00:08:56,160
I'd actually like to see it for myself.

158
00:08:56,244 --> 00:08:58,037
Unless, of course, you tell me otherwise.

159
00:08:58,788 --> 00:08:59,997
No, of course not.

160
00:09:07,755 --> 00:09:11,634
[man] The guard
marks the doors of the evacuees.

161
00:09:12,927 --> 00:09:14,387
Pretty standard procedure.

162
00:09:16,347 --> 00:09:18,474
Stop the car. I think I see someone.

163
00:09:20,184 --> 00:09:21,227
Stop the car.

164
00:09:22,687 --> 00:09:25,273
Madam President,
we’ll have someone circle back.

165
00:09:25,356 --> 00:09:26,566
Stop the car now.

166
00:09:36,075 --> 00:09:37,118
Damn it.

167
00:09:38,202 --> 00:09:39,704
Is she safe?

168
00:09:39,787 --> 00:09:41,998
Nothing is 100% safe.

169
00:09:57,471 --> 00:09:59,098
Hello. Anyone here?

170
00:10:23,914 --> 00:10:26,560
- [woman] The boy could have lost an eye.
- [man] That’s not how we treat people.

171
00:10:26,584 --> 00:10:28,520
- [woman] How could she?
- [man] My God, Elizabeth, stop it.

172
00:10:28,544 --> 00:10:30,147
[Elizabeth]
Am I raising a daughter or an animal?

173
00:10:30,171 --> 00:10:32,232
[man] They're the animals,
the way they attacked her.

174
00:10:32,256 --> 00:10:34,759
[Elizabeth]
Oh, of course, take her side. Of course!

175
00:10:34,842 --> 00:10:36,636
It's time she learned about the world.

176
00:10:36,969 --> 00:10:40,306
Pretty girls have a responsibility
to their beauty.

177
00:10:41,098 --> 00:10:43,184
I’ll bet she dared those boys.

178
00:10:43,643 --> 00:10:44,769
Shame on her.

179
00:10:45,853 --> 00:10:48,814
Why can't you just do as you're told?

180
00:10:49,982 --> 00:10:51,275
Why, indeed?

181
00:10:51,359 --> 00:10:54,278
Madam President! Madam President.

182
00:10:57,573 --> 00:10:58,908
Madam President...

183
00:11:00,493 --> 00:11:02,411
might be best if we head back.

184
00:11:03,621 --> 00:11:04,861
[Claire] So, the house is safe?

185
00:11:13,798 --> 00:11:14,882
Drink it then.

186
00:11:22,723 --> 00:11:23,891
I thought so.

187
00:11:41,033 --> 00:11:43,035
[indistinct chatter]

188
00:11:46,122 --> 00:11:48,749
- But what am I agreeing to?
- I can read it for you.

189
00:11:49,083 --> 00:11:50,083
I can read.

190
00:11:50,835 --> 00:11:52,044
And what's this for?

191
00:11:53,003 --> 00:11:55,631
That lets the app figure out
how we can be most helpful.

192
00:11:56,215 --> 00:11:59,552
It can be tailored to your specific needs.
We want to keep you informed.

193
00:11:59,635 --> 00:12:02,304
We want you to know what happens
before it happens.

194
00:12:02,847 --> 00:12:04,640
You can’t trust the government to do that.

195
00:12:04,724 --> 00:12:06,934
- Hello, my name is Seth Grayson.
- Nice to meet you.

196
00:12:07,017 --> 00:12:09,737
I'm with Shepherd Freedom Foundation,
can I talk to you for a second?

197
00:12:10,062 --> 00:12:14,191
[man] Sure thing. I was looking
at the pamphlet saying just...

198
00:12:16,694 --> 00:12:18,654
[indistinct chatter]

199
00:12:18,738 --> 00:12:19,989
[door closes]

200
00:12:20,072 --> 00:12:21,198
[woman] It's the president.

201
00:12:46,807 --> 00:12:48,184
Madam President.

202
00:12:49,518 --> 00:12:52,062
Whose idea was it? To leave it on his bed?

203
00:12:52,938 --> 00:12:54,106
Not here.

204
00:12:55,941 --> 00:12:58,903
The Shepherd Freedom Foundation
is here to help.

205
00:12:59,570 --> 00:13:03,240
The federal government is here
to help you.

206
00:13:03,824 --> 00:13:05,075
Yes, Madam President.

207
00:13:05,367 --> 00:13:09,288
The only way America’s problems
will be solved is through alliances

208
00:13:09,371 --> 00:13:12,875
between government and private industry,
each doing its part.

209
00:13:15,878 --> 00:13:17,671
The Commander in Chief and I go way back.

210
00:13:17,755 --> 00:13:20,216
We do. And I know I have
the full cooperation

211
00:13:20,299 --> 00:13:21,592
from the Shepherd family.

212
00:13:21,675 --> 00:13:25,930
The blatant disregard for human life
exhibited by companies like Arcas...

213
00:13:26,013 --> 00:13:28,682
Arcas is committed
to the safety of its workers.

214
00:13:29,016 --> 00:13:30,976
And with the help of...

215
00:13:31,477 --> 00:13:34,271
the right kind of legislation,
like the FUTURE Act.

216
00:13:34,355 --> 00:13:36,357
Which is under review at the moment.

217
00:13:37,024 --> 00:13:38,526
Until then,

218
00:13:38,609 --> 00:13:42,404
I am hereby moving
the EPA’s Criminal Investigative Division

219
00:13:42,488 --> 00:13:43,906
<i>into the Pentagon,</i>

220
00:13:44,490 --> 00:13:48,369
<i>where it will enjoy the forces
and the resources of our military.</i>

221
00:13:48,869 --> 00:13:51,205
<i>And they will investigate this disaster.</i>

222
00:13:51,914 --> 00:13:55,751
<i>I swear on my husband's grave,
I will find out what happened here.</i>

223
00:13:56,919 --> 00:13:58,671
<i>Thank you for your support.</i>

224
00:14:01,173 --> 00:14:03,853
I wanted to leave it on your bed.
Don't be thick, thick I can't use.

225
00:14:10,808 --> 00:14:12,810
[Marcus]
<i>Did she actually ask for a divorce?</i>

226
00:14:12,893 --> 00:14:15,855
- As if that matters.
- <i>And if I’m asked to justify the question?</i>

227
00:14:15,938 --> 00:14:18,566
It was justified the moment
they didn’t have an answer.

228
00:14:19,608 --> 00:14:22,945
The last thing the president wants is
to be talking about the former president.

229
00:14:23,028 --> 00:14:24,238
<i>Let me ask you this.</i>

230
00:14:24,321 --> 00:14:25,322
How did your mother feel

231
00:14:25,406 --> 00:14:27,658
when the president
yanked her hand away like that?

232
00:14:27,741 --> 00:14:29,952
<i>That's none of your goddamn business,
Marcus.</i>

233
00:14:30,578 --> 00:14:31,662
[beeps]

234
00:14:33,789 --> 00:14:36,101
- [man] Recoil? Is that the word you used?
- [Hammerschmidt] Yeah, that's what I see.

235
00:14:36,125 --> 00:14:37,352
- [woman] Are you kidding me?
- [Hammerschmidt] No.

236
00:14:37,376 --> 00:14:40,504
Are we really gonna waste time
dissecting a gesture between two women?

237
00:14:40,588 --> 00:14:42,715
Nora’s right. I was there.
There wasn't a recoil.

238
00:14:42,798 --> 00:14:44,383
I gotta agree with Tom here. For me,

