488
00:27:16,426 --> 00:27:17,927
for the last week or so.

489
00:27:18,011 --> 00:27:20,555
- Hired by who?
- We don't know yet.

490
00:27:21,056 --> 00:27:23,409
But they're making enough
so that one of them just purchased

491
00:27:23,433 --> 00:27:25,185
a second home on the Chesapeake Bay.

492
00:27:27,145 --> 00:27:28,145
They...

493
00:27:28,897 --> 00:27:31,024
broke into your Gaffney residence, ma’am.

494
00:27:32,067 --> 00:27:34,527
What? Where was Secret Service?

495
00:27:34,611 --> 00:27:35,945
And why wasn’t I alerted?

496
00:27:36,571 --> 00:27:38,031
Because no one was alerted.

497
00:27:38,114 --> 00:27:40,450
They left it completely untouched,

498
00:27:40,533 --> 00:27:41,951
as far as anyone can tell.

499
00:27:44,037 --> 00:27:46,039
How did you know anyone was there, then?

500
00:27:46,331 --> 00:27:50,251
An insomniac neighbor who spotted
the light from a phone screen inside.

501
00:27:52,462 --> 00:27:54,506
Taking pictures, I’m assuming.

502
00:27:55,090 --> 00:27:56,383
My, my, my.

503
00:27:56,466 --> 00:27:59,052
Night life in Gaffney
certainly has picked up.

504
00:28:04,265 --> 00:28:05,600
[laughs]

505
00:28:06,351 --> 00:28:08,269
Started when I was a kid.

506
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:10,689
Whenever the opportunity
would present itself,

507
00:28:10,772 --> 00:28:14,359
I’d slip my hand into a coat pocket
to see what I could find.

508
00:28:15,735 --> 00:28:18,613
A stranger’s pocket is a window
into his soul.

509
00:28:19,823 --> 00:28:21,783
And what did you find?

510
00:28:23,785 --> 00:28:24,828
Condoms.

511
00:28:25,203 --> 00:28:27,622
- [chuckles]
- Mints. Keys.

512
00:28:28,540 --> 00:28:31,000
Did you steal what you found?

513
00:28:31,918 --> 00:28:34,337
Not the mints.
Because that would be cruel.

514
00:28:34,421 --> 00:28:35,547
[Usher laughs]

515
00:28:36,923 --> 00:28:37,966
Was that you...

516
00:28:39,467 --> 00:28:40,719
on the way to the airport?

517
00:28:40,802 --> 00:28:42,846
Were you trying to teach her a lesson?

518
00:28:43,179 --> 00:28:44,472
- Talk to Bill.
- Come on.

519
00:28:44,556 --> 00:28:46,099
I already did.

520
00:28:49,519 --> 00:28:51,646
- She's late.
- Yeah, she’s the president.

521
00:28:52,147 --> 00:28:54,774
You know, you have a weakness
for strong women.

522
00:28:54,858 --> 00:28:55,858
Oh.

523
00:28:55,942 --> 00:28:56,943
No, really.

524
00:28:59,028 --> 00:29:00,739
You think they need your help.

525
00:29:06,870 --> 00:29:08,121
Really?

526
00:29:08,204 --> 00:29:09,998
- Still?
- No, no.

527
00:29:10,707 --> 00:29:11,916
I chew now.

528
00:29:12,834 --> 00:29:13,835
I just like to...

529
00:29:14,627 --> 00:29:15,670
play with this.

530
00:29:18,256 --> 00:29:20,008
- [cell phone ringing]
- Wait.

531
00:29:23,386 --> 00:29:24,386
She's here.

532
00:29:46,159 --> 00:29:48,828
Madam President, Duncan Shepherd.

533
00:29:49,662 --> 00:29:52,081
- Oh. Hello.
- [Annette] Claire.

534
00:29:53,291 --> 00:29:54,291
Annette.

535
00:29:55,126 --> 00:29:56,711
I see you've met Duncan.

536
00:29:57,587 --> 00:29:59,464
- Shall we?
- Yes.

537
00:30:04,469 --> 00:30:06,930
Don’t ever recoil from me again.

538
00:30:12,018 --> 00:30:14,854
[jazz music playing, indistinct chatter]

539
00:30:19,275 --> 00:30:21,611
- Ain’t 50 nifty?
- Mm-hmm.

540
00:30:22,654 --> 00:30:25,240
I think the last time you dragged me
into a bathroom,

541
00:30:25,323 --> 00:30:26,908
it was to show off your hickey.

542
00:30:27,325 --> 00:30:29,327
[laughs]

543
00:30:31,079 --> 00:30:33,623
I don’t think your brother
is gonna let up, Annette.

544
00:30:34,415 --> 00:30:37,252
Until he gets his ring kissed directly,
I think.

545
00:30:39,254 --> 00:30:41,631
Reminds me of someone you were married to.

546
00:30:41,714 --> 00:30:45,468
Oh, no. Bill and Francis
are very different people.

547
00:30:45,552 --> 00:30:46,553
Agreed.

548
00:30:49,264 --> 00:30:51,099
You know I slept with him once.

549
00:30:51,975 --> 00:30:52,975
Your brother?

550
00:30:54,143 --> 00:30:55,228
Your husband.

551
00:30:56,938 --> 00:30:57,938
I know.

552
00:30:59,524 --> 00:31:00,859
Interesting.

553
00:31:01,609 --> 00:31:03,736
Though, come to think of it,
I guess it makes sense.

554
00:31:05,280 --> 00:31:06,280
What does?

555
00:31:07,448 --> 00:31:09,868
That your marriage allowed for that.

556
00:31:11,953 --> 00:31:13,997
Well, it was the '98 campaign.

557
00:31:14,080 --> 00:31:17,000
Francis was facing a robust challenger,

558
00:31:17,083 --> 00:31:20,253
and there you were
at some DC fundraiser or other.

559
00:31:20,336 --> 00:31:22,046
It was at the Union Station,

560
00:31:22,130 --> 00:31:23,131
- East Hall.
- Yes.

561
00:31:23,214 --> 00:31:24,934
And there you were,
dangling your checkbook.

562
00:31:25,550 --> 00:31:28,177
So, it sounds like a favorable transaction
all around.

563
00:31:28,261 --> 00:31:31,180
- Is that what he told you?
- I never asked for details.

564
00:31:31,598 --> 00:31:33,391
I mean, I was curious.

565
00:31:33,474 --> 00:31:35,018
I really was.

566
00:31:35,560 --> 00:31:37,145
He was a good kisser, I’ll say that.

567
00:31:37,228 --> 00:31:40,815
But then the rest
was so underwhelming.

568
00:31:41,232 --> 00:31:43,276
Felt like he wasn’t all there.

569
00:31:43,526 --> 00:31:44,694
Like, he wasn't...

570
00:31:45,361 --> 00:31:46,821
all in, so to speak.

571
00:31:47,614 --> 00:31:49,824
Of course, my first thought, and...

572
00:31:50,950 --> 00:31:52,243
isn’t this true of most women?

573
00:31:52,327 --> 00:31:53,828
Was to wonder if it was me.

574
00:31:53,912 --> 00:31:58,791
Was I somehow less skilled
than I like to believe I am?

575
00:32:00,251 --> 00:32:02,545
Well, I can’t really answer to that,
Annette.

576
00:32:03,254 --> 00:32:04,254
I can.

577
00:32:04,881 --> 00:32:06,007
It was him.

578
00:32:08,259 --> 00:32:09,259
And...

579
00:32:10,303 --> 00:32:12,513
I bet it was never very different
with you.

580
00:32:14,307 --> 00:32:15,391
Even you.

581
00:32:15,934 --> 00:32:17,477
The blonde goddess.

582
00:32:18,186 --> 00:32:20,772
Even with you. Am I right?

583
00:32:23,566 --> 00:32:24,566
Wow.

584
00:32:26,027 --> 00:32:28,112
It's really only dawning on me now.

585
00:32:28,988 --> 00:32:30,740
The sacrifice you made.

586
00:32:32,325 --> 00:32:33,785
I sort of pity you.

587
00:32:33,868 --> 00:32:37,372
What you must have denied yourself
all those years.

588
00:32:37,455 --> 00:32:40,375
And this is where I tell you
to shut your mouth, Annette.

589
00:32:41,459 --> 00:32:43,503
You don't know anything about marriage,

590
00:32:44,003 --> 00:32:45,129
much less mine.

591
00:32:46,339 --> 00:32:48,716
Tell yourself whatever you want, Claire.

592
00:32:49,634 --> 00:32:51,052
We both know the truth.

593
00:32:52,261 --> 00:32:54,472
He’s waiting for you down the hall
in the prep kitchen.

594
00:32:57,350 --> 00:32:58,351
My brother.

595
00:32:59,519 --> 00:33:02,021
I can still do it by the way.

596
00:33:04,065 --> 00:33:05,065
Can you?

597
00:33:59,037 --> 00:34:00,277
[Bill] Well, you missed dinner.

598
00:34:01,456 --> 00:34:03,207
I can have 'em make you
whatever you like.

599
00:34:03,291 --> 00:34:04,375
I'm not hungry.

600
00:34:05,334 --> 00:34:06,753
The secret here is how much

601
00:34:07,128 --> 00:34:08,713
lemon juice you put in.

602
00:34:09,338 --> 00:34:10,840
Balance out the butter.

603
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:13,885
People and hollandaise.

604
00:34:13,968 --> 00:34:15,678
They think it tastes like money.

605
00:34:16,512 --> 00:34:19,140
- A night at the hotel.
- What where you looking for?

606
00:34:19,390 --> 00:34:22,310
There’s nothing in the Gaffney home
of value.

607
00:34:24,687 --> 00:34:25,980
Frank did things.

608
00:34:26,439 --> 00:34:27,607
And you just, what?

609
00:34:28,357 --> 00:34:29,442
Look the other way?

610
00:34:29,525 --> 00:34:32,904
That shot you took at me,
it’s not like you to be so reckless.

611
00:34:33,905 --> 00:34:35,281
You don’t scare easy.

612
00:34:36,657 --> 00:34:41,120
The future of our country is at stake.

613
00:34:42,163 --> 00:34:43,331
Does that sound...

614
00:34:44,040 --> 00:34:45,750
pat to you, naive?

615
00:34:46,834 --> 00:34:48,086
No, not at all.

616
00:34:49,003 --> 00:34:51,464
Do you think I don't have friends
at the Pentagon, Claire?

617
00:34:51,547 --> 00:34:54,884
You may want to make my four years
in office miserable...

618
00:34:54,967 --> 00:34:57,595
All I want you to do is behave,
as promised.

619
00:34:57,678 --> 00:35:01,099
You can dig up a ring or whatever else
you can get your hands on.

620
00:35:01,182 --> 00:35:05,019
But that doesn't mean I won't make
your time a living hell as well.

621
00:35:06,270 --> 00:35:08,272
[laughing]

622
00:35:09,148 --> 00:35:11,567
Raymond Tusk said about you one time,

623
00:35:11,651 --> 00:35:13,319
some dinner we were at,
he just said it...

624
00:35:13,402 --> 00:35:15,506
This is where I'm supposed
to be a little bit afraid of the answer,

625
00:35:15,530 --> 00:35:16,965
- I suppose.
- He said, "I don't know,

626
00:35:16,989 --> 00:35:18,699
whether or not she's a person...

627
00:35:20,535 --> 00:35:22,328
or just playing the part of one."

628
00:35:22,411 --> 00:35:26,165
And I thought it was so strange
at the time, but maybe it's true.

629
00:35:27,083 --> 00:35:28,083
Just...

630
00:35:30,545 --> 00:35:31,545
unreachable.

631
00:35:34,966 --> 00:35:36,509
I know it'll be hard for you.

632
00:35:38,052 --> 00:35:40,304
But you're going to have to treat me
as an equal, Bill.

633
00:35:44,267 --> 00:35:46,018
What did you do with your husband's will?

634
00:35:46,853 --> 00:35:48,771
[Claire] It was a revocable trust.

635
00:35:49,272 --> 00:35:50,272
All done.

636
00:35:50,314 --> 00:35:52,066
I'm not talking about that one.

637
00:35:53,109 --> 00:35:54,694
I'm talking about the other one.

638
00:35:55,278 --> 00:35:56,362
The new one.

639
00:35:57,488 --> 00:36:01,284
Bet Doug Stamper would love
to see the contents of that one.

640
00:36:02,618 --> 00:36:03,911
What's in there anyway?

641
00:36:04,620 --> 00:36:07,707
That you would go to such lengths

642
00:36:08,457 --> 00:36:09,876
to keep him from it?

643
00:36:13,629 --> 00:36:15,214
Claire Hale has a secret.

644
00:36:19,677 --> 00:36:23,556
Douglas Stamper is meeting
with the US District Attorney

645
00:36:23,639 --> 00:36:24,974
as we speak.

646
00:36:26,142 --> 00:36:27,351
He's out, Claire.

647
00:36:28,477 --> 00:36:30,313
And he's not going back in.

648
00:36:31,981 --> 00:36:34,317
Now, you need my help.

649
00:36:35,568 --> 00:36:36,652
Later tonight,

650
00:36:37,862 --> 00:36:40,781
I'm going to watch you sign that bill

651
00:36:41,157 --> 00:36:43,159
that's sitting on your desk.

652
00:36:44,619 --> 00:36:45,828
"To the dead,

653
00:36:46,162 --> 00:36:48,289
a kingdom means nothing.

654
00:36:49,332 --> 00:36:52,376
They have their requiem and eternity."

655
00:36:53,044 --> 00:36:55,546
That's <i>Macbeth. </i>The opera, not the play.

656
00:36:56,631 --> 00:36:59,175
All you have to do now
is just go on out there

657
00:36:59,508 --> 00:37:01,510
with your oldest, dearest friend and...

658
00:37:03,012 --> 00:37:04,931
hold her hand up high.

659
00:37:20,321 --> 00:37:21,489
Madam President.

660
00:37:21,822 --> 00:37:24,242
You don’t really think
the military is irrelevant?

661
00:37:24,825 --> 00:37:29,497
I watched your confirmation
from my chambers for the UN.

662
00:37:29,956 --> 00:37:32,959
- Wasn't my finest hour.
- Well, he who laughs loudest...

663
00:37:33,042 --> 00:37:34,835
Or is it "laughs last"?

664
00:37:34,919 --> 00:37:36,587
"Last." "She."

665
00:37:37,171 --> 00:37:39,507
- Vincent Abruzzo.
- Ninth Circuit.

666
00:37:39,590 --> 00:37:41,842
I am no good at functions like this.

667
00:37:41,926 --> 00:37:47,014
I tend to find a chair at these things
and sit in it for the rest of the evening.

668
00:37:47,098 --> 00:37:49,558
- Madam President.
- Yes. Well, it's been a pleasure.

669
00:37:49,642 --> 00:37:51,811
Madam President, if I may say,

670
00:37:51,894 --> 00:37:55,481
I'm so glad that we finally have a woman
in the Oval Office.

671
00:37:55,564 --> 00:37:58,150
The arc of history is long, but...

672
00:37:58,609 --> 00:38:01,279
The reign of the middle-aged white man
is over.

673
00:38:01,904 --> 00:38:05,283
The Bill Shepherds of the world
who won’t let go, have to go.

674
00:38:12,748 --> 00:38:16,168
Does anyone except you know about
the document that came for him?

675
00:38:16,460 --> 00:38:17,837
[Rosen] <i>No, of course not.</i>

676
00:38:18,921 --> 00:38:21,215
Because if anyone else
gets their hand on that will...

677
00:38:21,299 --> 00:38:23,092
<i>That is strictly between us.</i>

678
00:38:23,175 --> 00:38:25,011
We only just discovered
that he was missing.

679
00:38:25,636 --> 00:38:28,222
I put a call into the US Attorney
and was just informed

680
00:38:28,306 --> 00:38:29,765
charges have been dropped.

681
00:38:30,641 --> 00:38:32,018
How is that even possible?

682
00:38:32,101 --> 00:38:34,645
<i>I thought I’d lost my phone
a couple of days ago, but...</i>

683
00:38:35,313 --> 00:38:38,607
<i>But now I'm certain that he took it
and reached out to make a deal.</i>

684
00:38:39,525 --> 00:38:41,527
I can have a grand jury impaneled

685
00:38:41,610 --> 00:38:44,780
and we can be taking testimony
from witnesses within a week.

686
00:38:46,657 --> 00:38:47,700
Who do you have?

687
00:38:48,451 --> 00:38:49,827
Secretary Durant?

688
00:38:51,787 --> 00:38:52,788
And others.

689
00:38:55,041 --> 00:38:58,419
I'm sure I don't need to talk to you
about what's right or wrong.

690
00:38:58,878 --> 00:39:01,505
But in my experience,
most people, in the end,

691
00:39:01,589 --> 00:39:03,758
will do whatever they need to,
to save themselves.

692
00:39:12,516 --> 00:39:14,560
Do you think you have
a strong enough case?

693
00:39:15,353 --> 00:39:16,729
That depends on you.

694
00:39:17,396 --> 00:39:20,775
If I'm gonna put myself on the line,
I need to know you're going to win.

695
00:39:20,858 --> 00:39:22,777
This can be a very unforgiving town.

696
00:39:22,860 --> 00:39:24,570
I'm giving you a chance to start over.

697
00:39:26,947 --> 00:39:28,991
- Come on.
- I can offer you immunity

698
00:39:29,075 --> 00:39:30,242
for your testimony.

699
00:39:31,452 --> 00:39:34,455
But, Mr. Stamper, of course,
I can't give you any guarantees

700
00:39:34,538 --> 00:39:37,792
when it comes to your reputation
or that of the former president.

701
00:39:38,834 --> 00:39:40,961
You would have to testify
in an open court.

702
00:39:41,712 --> 00:39:42,713
That is the deal.

703
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:50,554
I should consult with my lawyers.

704
00:39:53,808 --> 00:39:55,643
Thank you for your time, Mr. Stamper.

705
00:40:06,362 --> 00:40:09,073
[woman] <i>Join us in supporting</i>
<i>the Dallas Scholarship Fund</i>

706
00:40:09,156 --> 00:40:10,366
<i>for Young Women:</i>

707
00:40:10,449 --> 00:40:11,534
<i>Take aim.</i>

708
00:40:26,257 --> 00:40:28,926
Look at these marvelous faces.

709
00:40:29,009 --> 00:40:31,053
The faces of our future.

710
00:40:31,720 --> 00:40:34,932
And I am so, so honored

711
00:40:35,015 --> 00:40:37,852
to be chosen to introduce to you

712
00:40:37,935 --> 00:40:41,355
the President of the United States,
Claire Underwood.

713
00:40:50,656 --> 00:40:52,491
[cheering, applause continues]

714
00:41:07,715 --> 00:41:10,342
I look at these brilliant young women

715
00:41:10,426 --> 00:41:12,094
and words fail me.

716
00:41:14,930 --> 00:41:16,182
What's this?

717
00:41:16,265 --> 00:41:18,392
They gave us these.
What are they gonna do?

718
00:41:18,976 --> 00:41:20,686
Yeah, I'm not drinking the water,

719
00:41:20,769 --> 00:41:22,188
no fucking way, I'll tell you that.

720
00:41:22,771 --> 00:41:24,899
I'll go all the way to Canton to buy it,
if I have to.

721
00:41:25,357 --> 00:41:27,693
And... Mr. Grayson,

722
00:41:28,486 --> 00:41:30,821
what else did he tell you about the app?

723
00:41:30,905 --> 00:41:33,699
Nothing.
You can go online and check it out.

724
00:41:34,241 --> 00:41:37,578
'Cause a lot of people I know signed up
for it even after the president left.

725
00:41:37,661 --> 00:41:38,661
Hmm.

726
00:41:42,041 --> 00:41:43,041
He said...

727
00:41:45,002 --> 00:41:46,002
Mr. Grayson?

728
00:41:48,047 --> 00:41:49,298
Yeah, him.

729
00:41:50,466 --> 00:41:52,510
That they were gonna tell us
what was gonna happen

730
00:41:52,593 --> 00:41:54,220
- before it happens.
- How?

731
00:41:56,222 --> 00:41:58,140
Look, I don't know.

732
00:41:59,099 --> 00:42:01,560
Ithaca's, like, where?

733
00:42:02,686 --> 00:42:04,230
There’s one in Greece.

734
00:42:04,438 --> 00:42:06,315
And the other's in upstate New York.

735
00:42:07,441 --> 00:42:08,776
Guess which one I'm from.

736
00:42:08,859 --> 00:42:09,985
[both chuckle]

737
00:42:13,739 --> 00:42:16,242
It’s a paper, it comes out once a week.

738
00:42:24,124 --> 00:42:25,251
It was going to happen,

739
00:42:26,085 --> 00:42:27,336
because it happened before.

740
00:42:28,254 --> 00:42:30,422
We complained all the way
to the EPA, but...

741
00:42:31,048 --> 00:42:32,048
whatever.

742
00:42:32,925 --> 00:42:34,969
Only this time the explosion was bad.

743
00:42:35,052 --> 00:42:38,764
And yeah, some guys died.
And the company knew.

744
00:42:40,975 --> 00:42:41,975
They knew.

745
00:42:48,357 --> 00:42:50,818
[sirens wail in the distance,
Doug clears throat]

746
00:42:50,901 --> 00:42:51,901
[door shuts]

747
00:42:54,405 --> 00:42:55,614
[Claire] Welcome home.

748
00:43:06,959 --> 00:43:09,295
Good timing. I just put on coffee.

749
00:43:10,462 --> 00:43:11,589
A little late for coffee.

750
00:43:11,672 --> 00:43:13,757
Well, we have so much to talk about.

751
00:43:15,759 --> 00:43:17,261
I'm glad you're out, Doug.

752
00:43:17,344 --> 00:43:19,305
I don't know what you were doing in there.

753
00:43:19,388 --> 00:43:20,388
[Doug sighs]

754
00:43:21,348 --> 00:43:22,891
How's the US Attorney?

755
00:43:27,146 --> 00:43:29,565
Secretary Durant's
negotiating her appearance.

756
00:43:32,151 --> 00:43:33,360
And if...

757
00:43:33,819 --> 00:43:36,363
Cathy should somehow be dissuaded?

758
00:43:36,697 --> 00:43:39,033
- Silenced?
- Then it all goes away.

759
00:43:40,492 --> 00:43:42,411
Yes, but they'll still want to know

760
00:43:43,037 --> 00:43:44,830
who knew what, when.

761
00:43:47,416 --> 00:43:48,626
I feel pretty clear.

762
00:43:51,378 --> 00:43:53,339
You think it was me
who asked you to take the fall

763
00:43:53,422 --> 00:43:56,508
- just because I said the words, right?
- He told me it was you.

764
00:43:56,592 --> 00:43:58,927
- He whispered it in my ear.
- And you believed him.

765
00:43:59,011 --> 00:44:00,346
Like you always believed him.

766
00:44:01,930 --> 00:44:05,100
Well, here’s what I believe.
Zoe Barnes killed herself...

767
00:44:05,184 --> 00:44:07,394
And I expected to be pardoned
for the rest.

768
00:44:07,478 --> 00:44:09,980
Since his death, my hands have been tied.

769
00:44:10,064 --> 00:44:11,231
[Doug scoffs]

770
00:44:11,315 --> 00:44:13,817
But I believe the universe
has given us a gift.

771
00:44:15,861 --> 00:44:17,363
I don't know what that means.

772
00:44:18,405 --> 00:44:19,406
Well...

773
00:44:21,116 --> 00:44:23,356
We both lost someone who shaped
the course of our lives.

774
00:44:26,413 --> 00:44:28,832
For good, but also for ill.

775
00:44:30,125 --> 00:44:31,543
And now here we are

776
00:44:32,586 --> 00:44:34,213
unexpectedly free.

777
00:44:36,131 --> 00:44:37,549
To take a different tack.

778
00:44:41,845 --> 00:44:43,931
We can do whatever we want, Doug.

779
00:44:45,974 --> 00:44:47,893
And we’ve been entwined, you and I,

780
00:44:48,435 --> 00:44:49,436
like it or not,

781
00:44:50,145 --> 00:44:51,438
for decades now.

782
00:44:51,939 --> 00:44:53,023
But I think...

783
00:44:54,233 --> 00:44:56,193
we deserve to go our separate ways.

784
00:44:57,778 --> 00:45:01,865
The only problem is we have something
urgent to attend to called Cathy Durant.

785
00:45:03,951 --> 00:45:06,078
And then we can finally be free.

786
00:45:08,455 --> 00:45:09,998
Do what we really want.

787
00:45:10,833 --> 00:45:12,251
Do what we need to do.

788
00:45:15,879 --> 00:45:17,756
What does Doug Stamper want?

789
00:45:18,716 --> 00:45:20,592
Are you trying to erase him?

790
00:45:22,428 --> 00:45:23,762
Because you can't.

791
00:45:24,430 --> 00:45:26,181
I’m not trying to do anything

792
00:45:26,265 --> 00:45:28,892
except be the sitting President
of the United States.

793
00:45:30,811 --> 00:45:32,730
It's wrong to assume

794
00:45:33,647 --> 00:45:36,650
Francis’s ambitions directly aligned
with mine, Doug.

795
00:45:38,152 --> 00:45:42,030
The best way to not to be associated
with his questionable deeds

796
00:45:42,114 --> 00:45:43,994
is to do good.
That’s what I plan to do, anyway.

797
00:45:45,492 --> 00:45:47,911
[Doug laughing]

798
00:45:50,664 --> 00:45:52,332
[Claire] Oh, you find that funny, do you?

799
00:45:53,125 --> 00:45:54,293
Well, it's true.

800
00:45:59,882 --> 00:46:02,134
I never understood what he saw in you.

801
00:46:03,177 --> 00:46:04,720
I mean the outside, sure.

802
00:46:06,138 --> 00:46:07,306
But the inside...

803
00:46:08,891 --> 00:46:10,726
- LeAnn’s death.
- No.

804
00:46:12,144 --> 00:46:13,395
You never cared for her.

805
00:46:13,479 --> 00:46:14,980
It wasn't necessary.

806
00:46:15,981 --> 00:46:17,274
And I told him so.

807
00:46:18,233 --> 00:46:19,318
And yet...

808
00:46:26,950 --> 00:46:28,494
Doug, do me a favor.

809
00:46:33,624 --> 00:46:34,792
Close your eyes.

810
00:46:36,752 --> 00:46:37,753
Please.

811
00:46:50,057 --> 00:46:51,642
He wanted you to have them.

812
00:47:37,020 --> 00:47:39,815
For this to happen
at this point in your life,

813
00:47:39,898 --> 00:47:41,817
the prognosis is not good.

814
00:47:43,819 --> 00:47:44,903
I know.

815
00:47:56,623 --> 00:47:58,458
Somebody killed Francis,

816
00:47:58,542 --> 00:48:00,335
and yet they don't want him to die.

817
00:48:01,086 --> 00:48:03,881
That last night, the last time we spoke,

818
00:48:03,964 --> 00:48:06,675
was when I declined his phone call
in the Oval Office.

819
00:48:07,718 --> 00:48:11,305
It had been close to two months,
and he was tired of waiting.

820
00:48:11,805 --> 00:48:14,391
So he showed up here in the White House.

821
00:48:14,766 --> 00:48:16,059
Like a thief.

822
00:48:16,685 --> 00:48:18,061
It was terrifying.

823
00:48:19,021 --> 00:48:21,064
He was furious, slurring his words.

824
00:48:21,148 --> 00:48:23,567
"Why can't you do as you're told, Claire?"

825
00:48:25,193 --> 00:48:27,946
I told the world that he died in our bed,

826
00:48:28,447 --> 00:48:29,907
but that's not the truth.

827
00:48:30,198 --> 00:48:32,326
I locked myself in my room that night,

828
00:48:32,409 --> 00:48:34,912
woke up in the morning
and found him dead in his.

829
00:48:37,497 --> 00:48:39,333
They killed him to shut me up.

830
00:48:41,335 --> 00:48:44,546
I need to bury Francis, once and for all.

831
00:49:05,025 --> 00:49:07,319
Do you need help signing it?

832
00:49:16,203 --> 00:49:18,413
No. Bill. Shepherd, enough.

833
00:49:20,791 --> 00:49:22,668
I actually have one condition.

834
00:49:26,171 --> 00:49:27,171
Put it back.

